He used the name Dinesen in the United States.  He is very specific in his journal that the name was and should remain spelled "Dinesen".  His children did not  maintain the name or spelling, consequently there are several variations of the name being used today.

attribution.changeMessage: The record is in the Church Book for Avnslev, Vindinge, Svensborg.  Familysearch's standardized place name is Skalkendrup, Aunslev, Vindinge, Svendborg, Denmark.  I am uncertain if "Aunslev" is a typo.  The record is a Baptism/Christening record on Palm Sunday in March of 1788 and they are using the "church holiday" system of dating.  In 1788 on the Danish calender, the full moon is 22 March so Easter Sunday is 23 March and Palm Sunday is on 16 March 1788.

attribution.changeMessage: Her Baptism record gives name as Ane Pedersdatter.  Her LDS Church membership Record gives her name as Anne Nielsen.

Ane was born a daughter of Peder Nielsen so patronymically her name was Ane Pedersdatter.  In 1828 a law was passed that required a surname inherited from the father.  Many believed the patronymic name sufficed.  Ane used Pedersdatter until she immigrated.  In the US she used Ane Nielsen at least when she got married.  Unfortunately, she cannot be traced genealogically as Nielsen.
1880 Danish Census gives her birth place as Kallehauge
